post_text: EXCITING NEWS for Searcy School District families!!! Beginning TOMORROW (Friday, September 4), ALL students enrolled in Searcy Public Schools (whether attending onsite or through Lions Online) will receive breakfast and lunch meals for FREE through December 31, 2020. According to the Division of Elementary and Secondary Education (DESE), this is due to a special United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) waiver. For any questions, please contact Charlotte Davis, District Child Nutrition Director at cdavis@searcyschools.org. #learningtogetherwhereverweare #searcyschools

post_text: The Searcy High School Boys Wrestling team and the Searcy High School Girls Wrestling team will be holding tryouts next Tuesday September 1st. Boys tryouts will be from 4:30 to 5:30 P.M. and Girls tryouts will be from 5:30 to 6:30 P.M. Any 9th through 12th grade student who wants to try out must email Coach Evans at evansj@searcyschools.org to be added to the tryout list. They must also have a current physical. Covid-19 school policies will be enforced, so all participants must wear a mask and bring a water bottle. Tryouts will be held in the wrestling room (Old Field House).

post_text: Searcy School District has been informed that three student athletes have tested positive for Covid 19. The Searcy High School football team has one positive case, and the SHS Lionsteppers have two members who tested positive. The administration and coaching staff followed the response protocol issued by The Division of Elementary and Secondary Education (DESE) and contacted the Arkansas Department of Health (ADH). We are currently in the process of notifying parents of those students who may have been in contact with the athletes. The district is taking active measures to deep clean and disinfect the athletic facilities appropriately. After consultation with the ADH, we were advised that due to appropriate documentation and protocols followed, practices may resume. Coaches will inform student athletes when their next practice will be held. Searcy School District remains committed to providing a safe and healthy learning environment during these uncertain times.

post_text: Searcy School District received notice of resignation from Searcy High School head football coach Mark Kelley today. Coach Kelley will be joining the Conway Wampus Cats coaching staff for the 2020 season. Coach Kelley led the Searcy Lions to their first state championship in its history last fall, and we are grateful for his dedication, winning spirit, and the rapport he developed with his student athletes. While we are disappointed to hear of his decision to leave Searcy School District, we want the best for Coach Kelley and wish him success as he continues his career in Arkansas high school football.

post_text: Searcy School District congratulates Christyn Henderson on being selected as the 2020-2021 Teacher of the Year! Mrs. Henderson teaches third grade at McRae Elementary School. Her innovative ideas, ability to teach students at all levels, willingness to continue learning herself and embrace new technology, and her positive attitude are just some of the reasons Mrs. Henderson was named as the district teacher of the year. Mrs. Henderson loves her students and her profession, and she demonstrates it every day with her smiling face and kind words for students and colleagues alike. Mrs. Henderson will participate in the Arkansas State Teacher of the Year competition in June. Again, we offer our congratulations!!

Searcy School District has been approved for a program called “Emergency Meals to You,” a partnership between USDA and Baylor University to benefit those in need of meal assistance during the COVID-19 pandemic. Any students who qualified for free or reduced-price meals during the current 2019-20 school year are eligible for this program. You may apply for shelf-stable meals to be shipped to your home for a few weeks after our Child Nutrition department finishes their meal distribution on May 18.You must apply online by Tuesday, May 12, 2020 to be eligible to receive these meals. The link to apply for this program is below. Thank you!

https://mealstoyou.org/emergency-meals-to-you-application/

post_text: On Saturday, April 25th, Governor Asa Hutchinson declared that no schools in Arkansas hold a traditional graduation ceremony before July 1st. Due to crowds and the need for social distancing, the first proposed graduation date of June 20th as well as the SHS prom on June 13th will not take place. At the present time, graduation on July 25th is still scheduled, but we will continue to follow the guidance of Governor Hutchinson and the Arkansas Department of Health.

post_text: Governor Asa Hutchinson and Secretary Johnny Key directed all schools to remain closed through the end of the 2019-2020 school year, and continue to participate in Alternative Methods of Instruction (AMI) until the end of the current school year. During that time, Searcy School District will postpone or provide alternate plans for activities such as prom and graduation. We will revisit plans to reschedule if Covid-19 restrictions are lifted. Our offices will be open on Mondays and Thursdays from 10:00 A.M.-2:30 P.M. We will continue to provide up-to-date information through phone messaging, social media, school website, and our mobile app.Thank you for your support!
text: Governor Asa Hutchinson and Secretary Johnny Key directed all schools to remain closed through the end of the 2019-2020 school year, and continue to participate in Alternative Methods of Instruction (AMI) until the end of the current school year. During that time, Searcy School District will postpone or provide alternate plans for activities such as prom and graduation. We will revisit plans to reschedule if Covid-19 restrictions are lifted. Our offices will be open on Mondays and Thursdays from 10:00 A.M.-2:30 P.M. We will continue to provide up-to-date information through phone messaging, social media, school website, and our mobile app.Thank you for your support!

post_text: It warms our hearts here at Searcy Public Schools to see our families making the best out of a difficult situation. Even Mrs. Marcita from Sidney Deener didn't let school closure affect her from greeting students this morning. She normally greets students in the car line, but this morning she did it through social media! Look at these students working on AMI. The Carrigan family made green pancakes and eggs as a science experiment on St. Patrick’s Day. We are so proud of you!!! Don't forget we are offering meals to all our students today! Check out our website or facebook page for the times. #cantstopthebeat #searcyschools

post_text: Searcy School District congratulates the March CAN'T STOP THE BEAT (CSTB) Award Winners! These employees demonstrate teamwork, encouragement to others, respect for others, and go the extra mile for their buildings and the Searcy School District students. We are proud to announce Charissa Hobby, Southwest Middle School dyslexia interventionist; Marcita Reynolds, Sidney Deener Elementary School paraprofessional; Lauren Taylor, Searcy High School math teacher; and Dee Williams, Southwest Middle School nurse, as the CSTB award winners this month! Superintendent Diane Barrett visited each today and presented them with a CSTB trophy and sweet treat!

post_text: So proud of the SHS Lady Lion Wrestling team!! State Champions!!!!
shared_text:
Searcy High School
February 21 at 3:34 PM ·

Congratulations to the SHS Lady Lions wrestlers on winning the first ever girls wrestling state tournament on Thursday February 20th. Matty Lincoln and Trinity Danberry won state titles in their weight divisions.

Other winners for Searcy were Harley Seymore - second place, and Lily Dias and Mykenzie Clark - third-place finishes in their weight divisions. Fourth-place finishers for the Lady Lions included Roselyn Amaya, Chloe Belford, and Vivi Edwards, while Ashley Coker was fifth in their weight classes.

Congratulations to our wrestlers and coaches!!!!

So proud of the SHS Lady Lion Wrestling team!! State Champions!!!!

Other winners for Searcy were Harley Seymore - second place, and Lily Dias and Mykenzie Clark - third-place finishes in their weight divisions. Fourth-place finishers for the Lady Lions included Roselyn Amaya, Chloe Belford, and Vivi Edwards, while Ashley Coker was fifth in their weight classes.

Congratulations to our wrestlers and coaches!!!!

post_text: Due to the overwhelming generosity of our community, the SHS Prom Closet has a full inventory of prom dresses. Because of the large inventory, we will not be accepting dresses for the rest of the year. We are, however, still accepting men's suits, ties, women's evening shoes, and costume jewelry and/or accessories. Please encourage any SHS student who would like to attend prom, but needs attire, to visit the SHS Prom Closet. Students may contact Betsy Bailey at bbailey@searcyschools.org or Sara Dacus at sdacus@searcyschools.org. We will have scheduled shopping days this spring. The SHS Prom is scheduled for Saturday, April 25. Again, we are forever grateful to our donors for the huge support of this project!

post_text: We were so pleased to host the Searcy Chamber of Commerce Leadership Institute participants yesterday. We hope the group enjoyed its time with us and that we could provide insight into the Searcy Public School District!
shared_text:
The Daily Citizen
January 15 at 10:26 AM ·

Ally Randolph/arandolph@thedailycitizen.com

Robotics students from Ahlf Junior High School walk up their robots to demonstrate their skills to the Searcy Leadership Institution Tuesday afternoon. According to the Searcy Regional Chamber of Commerce, since 1994, Leadership Searcy has acquainted “highly motivated” individuals with community needs.

The group met on Tuesday at the Searcy School District’s central office for its fourth session, which was themed “Education.” After the students made their presentation, members of the institute were given laptops and taught how to code.

https://www.thedailycitizen.com/

Brought to you by Unity Health https://unity-health.org/

post_text: Searcy School District congratulates the January CAN'T STOP THE BEAT (CSTB) Award Winners! These employees demonstrate teamwork, encouragement to others, respect for others, and go the extra mile for their buildings and the Searcy School District students. We are proud to announce LeeAnn Blount, Ahlf Junior High School counselor, Keith Crafton, Ahlf Junior High School paraprofessional, Wrennie Hawkins, Searcy High School child nutrition employee, and Amanda Price, Searcy School District literacy instructional facilitator, as the CSTB award winners this month! Superintendent Diane Barrett visited each today and presented them with a CSTB trophy and sweet treat!

post_text: Searcy School District would like to inform the public that if, and only if, the tornado sirens sound in this area, the Ahlf Jr. High School safe room on Elm Street will be open for shelter. post_text: Searcy School District congratulates the November CAN'T STOP THE BEAT (CSTB) Award Winners! These employees demonstrate teamwork, encouragement to others, respect for others, and go the extra mile for their buildings and the Searcy School District students. We are proud to announce Sidney Deener administrative assistant Ellie Lamb, Southwest Middle School G/T teacher Katie Lawson, Southwest Middle School paraprofessional Bill Fultz, and Westside Elementary School art teacher Cheryl Simmons as the CSTB award winners this month! Superintendent Diane Barrett visited each today and presented them with a CSTB trophy and sweet treat!

These employees demonstrate teamwork, encouragement to others, respect for others, and go the extra mile for their buildings and the Searcy School District students. We are proud to announce Sidney Deener administrative assistant Ellie Lamb, Southwest Middle School G/T teacher Katie Lawson, Southwest Middle School paraprofessional Bill Fultz, and Westside Elementary School art teacher Cheryl Simmons as the CSTB award winners this month! Superintendent Diane Barrett visited each today and presented them with a CSTB trophy and sweet treat!
